                    <persName xml:id="name1321-2" xml:lang="en" resp="http://syriaca.org" srophe:tags="#syriaca-headword">John of Edessa</persName>
                    <persName xml:id="name1321-6" xml:lang="en" resp="http://syriaca.org">John, the priest</persName>
                    <persName xml:id="name1321-3" xml:lang="fr-x-fiey" source="#bib1321-1">JEAN
                        D'EDESSE</persName>
                    <persName xml:id="name1321-4" xml:lang="fr-x-zanetti" source="#bib1321-7">Yōḥanān</persName>
                    <persName xml:id="name1321-5" xml:lang="fr" source="#bib1321-7">Jean le
                        prêtre</persName>
                    <idno type="URI">http://syriaca.org/person/1321</idno>
                    <idno type="FIEY">255</idno>
                    <note xml:lang="en" type="abstract" resp="http://syriaca.org" corresp="http://syriaca.org/persons http://syriaca.org/q http://syriaca.org/saints">In hagiography:
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/1321">John of Edessa</persName> was a priest from <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/78">Edessa</placeName> who nourished 12 holy men in a cave. He became
                        friends with <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/1405">Paul of
                            Edessa</persName>, his workman, who was actually a Latin bishop in
                        disguise. The two lived a life of prayer and spiritual companionship. They
                        travelled to <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/563">Sinai</placeName>. Back in <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/78">Edessa</placeName>, they interacted with <persName>Matthew the
                            eunuch</persName>, a woman hiding in a monastery. They travelled to
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/104">Jerusalem</placeName>.
                        Paul performed miracles and fled to <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/142">Nisibis</placeName>. John found him
                        there, and Paul told him to return to <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/78">Edessa</placeName>. Paul died, and
                        John died 8 months later. The story was set in the time of the <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/26">Bishop Rabbula of
                        Edessa</persName>.</note>
                    <floruit>
                        <date source="#bib1321-1" from="0418" srophe:computed-start="0418" to="0435" srophe:computed-end="0435">418-435</date>
                    </floruit>
